Container Runtime

A container runtime is the software component that runs containers on a host machine. It controls the entire container lifecycle, which includes creating, starting, stopping, and removing containers. In addition, it manages essential tasks such as resource isolation, filesystem configuration, and networking required for containers to operate correctly.

In simple terms, a container runtime acts as the engine that executes containerized applications.

Types of Container Runtime

Container runtimes are generally classified into two main categories:

High-Level Container Runtime

Low-Level Container Runtime

1. High-Level Container Runtime

A high-level container runtime provides convenient tools such as command-line interfaces (CLI), APIs, and management utilities that allow users to easily create and manage containers. These runtimes depend on low-level runtimes to perform the actual container execution.

Examples

Docker

containerd

CRI-O

Key Functions

Retrieve container images from container registries

Control the container lifecycle (create, run, stop, delete)

Provide command-line tools for user interaction

Integrate with orchestration platforms like Kubernetes

Handle container image storage and management

High-level runtimes primarily focus on ease of management and user interaction.

2. Low-Level Container Runtime

A low-level container runtime works directly with the Linux kernel to start and run containers. It performs the actual execution of containers by configuring kernel mechanisms that enable isolation and resource management.

These runtimes rely on Linux kernel capabilities such as:

Namespaces

cgroups

Filesystem isolation

Process execution

Examples

runc

crun

Kata Containers

Key Functions

Launch container processes

Configure namespaces to isolate system resources

Configure cgroups for CPU, memory, and resource control

Execute containers according to the standards defined by the Open Container Initiative

Low-level runtimes mainly focus on actual container execution and system isolation.

Container Runtime Architecture

The process of running a container typically follows these steps:

A user or orchestration system issues a command to run a container.

The high-level runtime processes the request.

The low-level runtime starts the container process.

The Linux kernel applies isolation using namespaces and cgroups.

The containerized application begins executing.

Summary
Type	Purpose	Examples
High-Level Runtime	Provides management tools and controls container lifecycle	Docker, containerd, CRI-O
Low-Level Runtime	Executes containers using kernel-level features	runc, crun, Kata Containers
Process Isolation in Containers

Process isolation ensures that each container operates as if it is running on its own system, even though multiple containers share the same operating system kernel.

This isolation prevents containers from:

Viewing processes running in other containers

Accessing files belonging to other containers

Interfering with system resources used by other containers

Process isolation is implemented using Linux namespaces.

Linux Namespaces

A namespace is a feature of the Linux kernel that isolates system resources for a specific group of processes.

Each container receives its own namespaces, which allows it to behave like a separate machine even though it shares the same host system.

Common namespaces used in containers include:

PID Namespace

Mount Namespace

UTS Namespace

User Namespace

PID Namespace

The PID namespace separates the process ID (PID) space for containers.

This means processes inside one container can only see the processes running within that same container.

How It Works

In Linux, every process is assigned a Process ID (PID). Normally, all processes share a single PID space.

When PID namespaces are used:

Each container maintains its own PID numbering system.

The first process started inside a container typically has PID 1.

Advantages

Process-level isolation

Containers cannot access processes of other containers

Improved security and stability

Mount Namespace

The mount namespace isolates the filesystem view of a container.

Each container can have its own root filesystem, which means it only sees the directories and files assigned to it.

Advantages

Filesystem separation

Secure file access

Independent root filesystem for each container

UTS Namespace

The UTS namespace isolates system identifiers such as:

Hostname

Domain name

UTS stands for Unix Time Sharing System.

How It Works

Each container can be assigned its own hostname that is different from the host machine.

For example:

Host system hostname → main-server

Container hostname → container-1

When the hostname command is executed inside the container, it displays the container’s hostname instead of the host machine’s hostname.

Advantages

Containers appear as independent systems

Useful for distributed and clustered environments

User Namespace

The user namespace separates user IDs (UID) and group IDs (GID) between the container and the host system.

How It Works

A user inside the container may appear as root, but this user is mapped to a non-root user on the host machine.

Example mapping:

Container User	Host User
root (UID 0)	UID 1000

This means:

Inside the container → the user has root privileges

On the host system → the user has limited permissions

Advantages

Improved security isolation

Prevents containers from obtaining real root access on the host machine

Conclusion

Container runtimes are responsible for executing containers and managing their lifecycle. They rely on Linux kernel mechanisms such as namespaces and cgroups to ensure isolation, security, and efficient resource utilization.

Namespaces are especially important because they isolate system resources like processes, filesystems, hostnames, and user identities, allowing multiple containers to operate independently while sharing the same operating system kernel.